🛠️ DevOps Lab Setup with Ansible (WSL + Ubuntu)
This guide helps you set up a DevOps lab using WSL, Ubuntu, and Ansible on a Windows system.

📌 Lab Requirements
Windows 10/11 system

Internet connection

⚙️ Step-by-Step Setup
✅ Step 1: Install WSL on Windows
Open PowerShell as Administrator.

Run the command:
```bash
wsl --install
✅ Step 2: Install Ubuntu on WSL
Open Microsoft Store.

Search for "Ubuntu App" (choose Ubuntu 22.04 LTS).
Click Install.

Open Ubuntu from the Start Menu.

Create a UNIX username and password when asked.

✅ Step 3: Update Ubuntu Packages
Run this command in the Ubuntu terminal:
```bash
sudo apt update -y
✅ Step 4: Install Ansible
Run this command in Ubuntu:

```bash
sudo apt install ansible -y
To check if Ansible was installed correctly, run:

```bash
ansible --version
🧪 Lab Execution: Configuration Management with Ansible
✅ Step 5: Create a Working Directory
Run the following commands:

```bash
mkdir ansible-lab
cd ansible-lab

✅ Step 6: Create the Inventory File
Use a text editor to create a file:

bash
Copy
Edit
vi inventory.ini
Add this content:

```bash
[local]
localhost ansible_connection=local

Press Esc, type :wq, then press Enter to save and exit.

✅ Step 7: Test Ansible Connectivity
Run this command:

```bash
ansible all -i inventory.ini -m ping

Expected Output:

```bash
localhost | SUCCESS => {
  "changed": false,
  "ping": "pong"
}
This means Ansible can talk to your local machine.

✅ Step 8: Create a Basic Playbook
Create a playbook file:

```bash
vi install_htop.yml

Add the following:

```bash
---
- name: Install htop system monitor tool
  hosts: local
  become: true

  tasks:
    - name: Install htop package
      ansible.builtin.package:
        name: htop
        state: present

```
Save and exit (Esc, type :wq, press Enter).

✅ Step 9: Run the Playbook
Run:
```bash
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini install_htop.yml
Expected Output:

```markdown
TASK [Install htop package] *****************************************
changed: [localhost]
✅ Step 10: Verify the Installation
Run:

nginx

You should see the htop system monitor interface. Press q to quit.

